        <h3>4-4-2 Diamond</h3>
        <p>
            The 4-4-2 Diamond provides no natural width because of the lack of wingers or wide midfielders and as such, 
            the fullbacks have the responsibility of pushing up on the overlap to exploit spaces in the wide areas.

            When on the attack, the diamond requires the deepest lying midfielder to hold position, as a shield to the defence — 
            a defence without the two fullbacks who have joined in the attack.

            The greatest strength of this formation comes from its ability to remain flexible and efficient in the central midfield areas. 
            The two central midfielders are required to be able to cover as much ground as possible while retaining shape and flexibility.

            A #10 without any significant defensive responsibility is utilised in an attempt to overload the central region and compensate for the lack of natural width.
            By having a dedicated defensive midfielder, some attacking is sacrified to ensure defensive stability.
            Through the use of four midfielders packed into the middle of the pitch, the diamond gives an edge over most other formations by having an extra man. 
            
            When the fullbacks go on the overlap to compensate for a lack of wide attacking players, the backline is left exposed to a potential counterattack.
            The Diamond requires extremely fit central midfielders to cover ground, and fullbacks who can bomb up and down the pitch with ease. 
            This may put a strain on the players, resulting in a possible decrease in efficiency over the course of the game or season.
        </p>
