    <div class="post" id="352">
        <h3>3-5-2</h3>
        <p>
            The 3-5-2 has two particular traits that separate it from all other football formations: a 3-man defence, and the use of wingbacks.

            In this system, the wingbacks although with defensive responsibilities, acts more as a midfielder, than as a defender. 
            They are required to roam up and down the flank to which he is assigned, acting as a winger when in attack, and as a fullback when in defence; hence the term, 'wingback'.

            Contrary to the idea that more is better, having three central defenders in place of the normal two can easily send things going south for the team. 
            As players are trained to defend in pairs, putting up a partnership of three defenders may result in confusion over average defensive positions and roles. 
            Generally, one of these three defenders is able to step up into defensive midfield and create from deep. 

            The 3-5-2 is particularly effective against attacking teams; 
            its ability to transform easily into a defensive 5-3-2 makes it the perfect formation for a team willing to sit back and hit on the break. 

            One of the 3-5-2's greatest strengths, unpredictability, may also be its greatest weakness. 
            A weakness shared by the 4-4-2 Diamond, playing without any advanced wide players puts a lot of strain on the wing backs, as they are required to attack, defend, and do both intelligently.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="post" id="433">
        <h3>4-3-3</h3>
        <p>
            The 4-3-3 is mostly used by possession-based teams with technical midfielders. 
            As such, the 4-3-3 can be used when winning a midfield battle is paramount in winning the game.

            The success of the 4-3-3 rests on the quality of the three midfielders available. Usually, the team lines up with one central defensive midfielder and two midfielders ahead of him. 

            This three man midfield is usually assigned three roles; the defender, the controller, and the creator. 
            The defender is the defensive midfielder who shields the defence, the controller sets the tempo of the game, and the creator links up the midfield with the forwards ahead of him.

            Unlike two-striker formations, the 4-3-3 has just one dedicated striker, so the presence of wide forwards who create plays cutting in from the flanks is needed to support the striker. 

            Keeping with the team of technically gifted players, this formation requires intelligent fullbacks who know when to attack on the overlap, or maintain defensive shape. 
            This is to prevent the players from being caught out of position unnecessarily. 

            The 4-3-3 is primarily designed for attack, and in the event of both fullbacks opting for the overlap at the same time, the team is left exposed with only three men at the back. 

            It is important to understand that the three central midfielders needed are required to have high technical skills, 
            a perfect fit between innovativeness and willingness to play specific roles.
        </p>
